<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-05-28T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-05-28T18:00:00-05:00" n="186" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">330/5–2551: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                                (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Austin</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-05-28T19:00:00-04:00">May 28,
                                    1951—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>951. Re <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 1584, May 25. Confirming
                            telephone conversation with Hyde,<note n="1" xml:id="d186fn1">James N.
                                Hyde, Adviser on Security Council Affairs, United States Mission at
                                the United Nations.</note>
                            <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> agrees with your helpful analysis
                            of situations which may arise in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> on
                            Chinese representation issue under Malik’s presidency.</p>
                        <p>We assume challenge of Malik’s ruling in Para 2(B) of <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> wld be on ground that president has
                            no power to make such ruling particularly in light of rule 17 of <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> Rules of Procedure.</p>
                        <p>We understand you will discuss in detail possible procedural situations
                            with friendly Dels and on basis of results will inform <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> whether approach to capitals
                                advisable.<note n="2" xml:id="d186fn2">No further action seems to
                                have occurred.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>